sentences: Susumu Matsushita (松下進 Matsushita Susumu; born February 6, 1950 in Fussa, Tokyo) is a Japanese manga artist known for his unique American comic–influenced design.

His most famous works are the designing of the mascots Neppie and Ripsea of the Orix Buffaloes, the concept art for the Monkey Magic television series, and video game artwork for Hudson's Adventure Island series (1986, NES), Motor Toon Grand Prix (1994, PS1), and Maximo: Ghosts to Glory (2001, PS2).

His most famous works are the designing of the mascots Neppie and Ripsea of the Orix Buffaloes, the concept art for the Monkey Magic television series, and video game artwork for Hudson's Adventure Island series (1986, NES), Motor Toon Grand Prix (1994, PS1), and Maximo: Ghosts to Glory (2001, PS2).
Born in early 1950, Susumu Matsushita developed an aptitude for artistic design at a young age.
Matsushita began working as a freelance graphic designer in 1973.
This was soon followed by a contract with Shueisha in 1979 to creating artwork for Young Jump.
Creating his own studio company in 1986, Matsushita immediately signed a contract with ASCII to produce covers for the video game magazine, Famicom Tsūshin (subsequently shortened to Famitsū).

Early years ==
Within a few months of experimentation he completely shifted to graphic design and the airbrush became his primary tool.
He had difficulties marketing himself initially, however his career gained momentum after securing a 1976 deal with Magazine House to produce magazine covers for the fashion magazine, Popeye.

Matsushita's development of Young Jump's mascot, Mac Bear (later Buddy Bear), was to provide a significant moment in his career as he would shift increasingly toward the development of characters and mascots.
